<br>
<br>
A gas cored power reactor<br>
<br>
I thought that I would explain how these ideas came to me. By explaining how I worked it out it will be easier for you to understand the extraordinary simplicity of the system<br>
<br>
Some time ago I read about an interesting phenomenon discovered quite accidentally by early plutonium workers. They observed that if they poured plutonium dust slowly into a container, a point would be reached where the surface would start to vibrate. The explanation for this was simple, if a little alarming. The vibration was caused by nuclear reactions. Once sufficient powder had been added to produce a just critical condition nuclear reactions would begin. This generated heat (and a dose of Neutrons) which caused the air trapped between the dust grains to expand, this forced the dust particles apart, reducing the density and rendering it sub critical, reactions would cease, the air would cool down and contract and the dust would collapse back to its original volume and density where reactions would begin again. This process, once established, would continue (almost) indefinitely in a state of dynamic stability. It occurred to me that if a gaseous version of the same process was possible, it would have enormous potential for the safe development of civil nuclear power<br>
<br>
The Basic Gas Reactor<br>
<br>
Please note-This is a conceptual design<br>
<br>
<br>
(There was originally a picture here, but I don't know how to post pictures yet, You'l have to immagine it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   )<br>
<br>
                 <br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Vc=&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp a spherical chamber that would contain just enough UF6 gas at atmospheric pressure to enable Fission to take place.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Vt=&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp an additional volume in a cylinder above and connected to the main vessal to allow an operating fuel reserve. For this example its contribution to the fission in the main chamber will be ignored<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Mp=&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Gastight Piston, free to move within the control tube Vt having a mass M<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Consider M=0<br>
<br>
The gas in the reaction chamber is at atmospheric pressure, there is no heat loss or gain from the reaction chamber, no significant nuclear reactions take place and the temperature remains at room temperature (say 300K).<br>
<br>
Consider that the weight of Mp is raised slowly until the pressure increases to 3 Atm(abs) <br>
<br>
As The piston begins to move down the tube towards the reaction chamber, the gas, which is initially at room temperature (300K) is compressed, this reduces the total volume Vc+Vt and increases the Density of the gas within Vc to a supercritical condition. Nuclear reactions will increase at an accelerating rate, increasing the temperature and pressure in the reaction chamber  until the piston is pushed back to its starting position at Op,  <br>
<br>
Once this point is reached the reactor will no longer be supercritical and the rate of reaction increase will drop to zero with the new equilibrium reaction rate will be just sufficient to maintain the new operating temperature of 900K against heat losses from the chamber. The operating pressure at this new temperature will only be 30PSI over ambient.<br>
<br>
<br>
The startling thing about this dynamic equilibrium is that the SOLE controlling factor is the weight of the piston Mp, Once the required operating temperature has been established and the and the corresponding piston weight calculated and put in place, no further controls are needed.<br>
<br>
If the rate of heat loss from the reaction chamber is increased, say to boil water to drive a turbine, then initially the gas will be cooled, this allows it to contract increasing the density within the reaction chamber and thus the rate of nuclear reactions, the temperature rises once more, expanding the gas, raising the piston back to the operating point where a new equilibrium is established with a higher reaction rate to take account of the increased heat loss.<br>
<br>
Conversely if the heat demand falls due to, say a reduction in the demand for electricity from the generators or even a complete failure in the cooling system (which could melt a conventional reactor).The surplus heat would initially raise the gas temperature and hence the pressure, this lifts the piston above the equilibrium point, once the piston is raised above Op the gas in the reaction chamber will become sub critical and will no longer sustain Nuclear fission and Reactions will rapidly decrease and, although the gas temperature is still around 900K, it will not rise significantly above this. The amount of heat left in the system will be represented only by the thermal capacity of a couple of cubic meters of UF6 gas, the body of the reaction chamber, and the decay heat of any waste materials present.<br>
<br>
A serious runaway Nuclear reaction is impossible, a meltdown is impossible, the reaction is entirely self regulated and automatically takes account of all external factors. Operators need only concern themselves with the operation of the non-nuclear components of the power station confident in the knowledge that the reactor will respond safely and predictably to anything that they may do, correct or incorrect. the piston weight defines the reactor temperature and never needs to be adjusted,<br>
<br>
<br>
In practice as the fuel is used up. The equilibrium temperature will fall, since the reduction of the proportion of fissionable material in the gas will increase the density required for criticality. And over a period of time the accumulation  of  decay products will not only poison the reactor to some extent but also represent  an increasing thermal hazard if there is loss of cooling. However the UF6 can be circulated through the reactor and continuously scrubbed and replenished. Thus we not only have a reactor core with virtually no fission fragments present (ie no nasty pollution in the unlikely event of an escape) but also one where the reprocessing is done at the same time reducing costs considerably. For added safty we could also have the scram systems discussed in the Lightbulb NTR. Its worth considering that if the safety and reliability of Gas cored reactors can be established in a power plant people may be more willing to accept it in a rocket.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
