<br>
Whereas in initial reactors and most Soviet designs the Temperature Coefficient in the reactor design is positive, meaning an uncontrollable reaction will occur if cooling control is lost, the vast majority of reactors in use in the US today were designed with a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> negative</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Temperature Coefficient.<br>
<br>
What does this mean? Can we just let the equation for the reactivity coefficient sort itself out, since one of the four factors in it varies negatively with increasing Temperature?<br>
<br>
Well, I wouldn't advise it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   The other safety systems in place in US plants are very worthwhile, because they ensure that there is no radiation leak and that the water in the system doesn't boil and thus create problems that way(denucleate boiling is one of the huge design-basis problems).<br>
