<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://web.ead.anl.gov/uranium/guide/ucompound/propertiesu/hexafluoride.cfm">web.ead.anl.gov/uranium/g...uoride.cfm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Basically, if you are concerned with UF6 getting out of the core, you vent it into a backup tank using a rupture valve.  As the pressure drops, it changes to a solid.  Since it will precipitate all over, it will still go to deep non-criticality.  Problem solved.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
If it STILL escapes, you set up sprinklers on the inside of your containment.  As the UF6 gets out, you hit it with water, causing it to convert to the solid UO2F2 form.  Of course, this generates hydroflouric acid as a side effect, so it might be wise to spike the water with some baking soda or similar base.  <br>
<br>
Of course there will be a containment structure around all of this.   Seems only prudent.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
